    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1810_04_04_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline> 
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</placeName><note>37</note>
                        <date when="1810-04-04">April 4.<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1810</date>
                        </dateline>
                    
                    My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Sir,</persName></opener>
                <p>
                    We have just read Sir <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RomiS1">Samuel Romilly's</persName><lb/>
                    <title ref="./Workography.xml#Obser1" cert="medium">speech</title> upon criminal law; and I do not<lb/>
                    know sufficiently <add>how</add> to admire his patience in<lb/>
                    making clear to the meanest capacities truths<lb/>
                    which appear almost self-evident when put <choice><orig>in-<lb/>
                    to</orig><reg>into</reg></choice> the form of propositions. To contradict them<lb/>
                    is metaphysically impossible - But not <choice><orig>physi-<lb/>
                    cally</orig><reg>physically</reg></choice> - for there are many who like the statue<lb/>
                    of Memnon always make a noise when the<lb/>
                    sun rises - I particularly admire the <choice><orig>plain-<lb/>
                    ness</orig><reg>plainnness</reg></choice> of manner with which the author lays<lb/>
                    the facts before the mind. It is evident that<lb/>
                    it is not for want of oratorical talents that<lb/>
                    he is thus plain,<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    "Graced as he is with all the power of words"<lb/>
                    He allows some eloquence to appear in the<lb/>
                    notes - So have I have seen dainties at a quaker's<lb/>
                    side table which he was too proud to produce<lb/>
                    for the entertainment of his principal guests.<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    I am comforted for having <choice><orig>inadvertent<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1810_04_04_page02.jpg"/>
                    -ly</orig><reg>inadvertently</reg></choice> recommended <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PaleW1">Paley</persName> without proper<lb/>
                    restrictions in <title ref="./Workography.xml#Proff1">Prof: Ed</title>: by seeing that Sir<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RomiS1">Samuel Romilly</persName> finds it necessary to write<lb/>
                    so much against the authority of his name,<lb/>
                    and to refute some of his arguments which<lb/>
                    are really as weak as those of a child. I think<lb/>
                    Sir <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RomiS1">Samuel</persName> has bestowed too much attention<lb/>
                    upon -and "thrice he slays the slain" -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RomiS1">Sir S.</persName> has also I see bestowed much <choice><orig>atten-<lb/>
                     tion</orig><reg>attention</reg></choice>, - and to good purpose, upon <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentJ1">Bentham</persName><lb/>
                     and C<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>. (see all the ideas on the injustice &amp; inutility<lb/>
                     of mercy - the <hi rend="underline">promulgation</hi> of laws - the <hi rend="underline">glorious</hi><lb/>
                    uncertainty of the law - the satisfaction of vengeance &amp;c<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    You see my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Sir</persName> that what I<lb/>
                    have prophesied will be accomplished, that<lb/>
                    all the ideas in <title ref="./Workography.xml#Theor4" cert="medium">"<hi rend="underline">The</hi> Treatise on Legislation</title>" will<lb/>
                    by degrees be popularised by succeeding authors<lb/>
                    in various forms, and that when the coin gets<lb/>
                    into common and universal use, the richness<lb/>
                    of the original mine, and the power, and skill<lb/>
                    with which it was <del>originall</del> first worked will<lb/>
                    become more and more the objects of admiration<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    The vulgar ideas of justice = vengeance<lb/>
                    = &amp; mercy are partly of religious and partly of<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1810_04_04_page03.jpg"/>
                    <note>38</note>
                    patriarchal origin. In the patriarchal government<lb/>
                    which, you know, is said to be the prototype of all<lb/>
                    others, the offences of the children were not only<lb/>
                    punished to prevent future evil, and disorder, but<lb/>
                    as being offences against the father, as instances of<lb/>
                    disrespect to him - exciting his anger &amp;c. - If he <choice><orig>re-<lb/>
                    -mitted</orig><reg>remitted</reg></choice> that part of the punishment, which regarded<lb/>
                    himself this was mercy - then following the <choice><orig>ana-<lb/>
                    logy</orig><reg>analogy</reg></choice> the King represents the father of his people<lb/>
                    and according to the fiction, and according to<lb/>
                    the actual technical forms &amp; terms of our law<lb/>
                    every breach of the peace is <choice><orig>stiled</orig><reg>styled</reg></choice> an offence against<lb/>
                    our Sovereign Lord the King - Then the King is <choice><orig>fa-<lb/>
                    -ther</orig><reg>father</reg></choice> like to shew mercy - Thus false analogies<lb/>
                    once admitted produce innumerable errors not<lb/>
                    only in abstract reasoning but in the general<lb/>
                    business. The argument respecting our judges &amp;<lb/>
                    their discretionary power of mercy might I think<lb/>
                    be put shortly thus<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    If the discretionary power left in the hands<lb/>
                    of judges be not exercised justly, - it is cruelty - if it<lb/>
                    be exercised justly why not make it law? -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    In fact where laws are too severe or<lb/>
                    in any respect inadequate there must always<lb/>
                    be a struggle between opinion &amp; Law - Law<lb/>
                    being founded on past experience &amp; opinion <choice><orig>aris<lb/>
                    ing</orig><reg>arising</reg></choice> from present or passing circumstances -<lb/>
                    whenever <hi rend="underline">the opinion</hi> becomes general <hi rend="underline">the law</hi><lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1810_04_04_page04.jpg"/>
                    must change - I can therefore make no doubt<lb/>
                    of Sir <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RomiS1">Samuel Romilly's</persName> affecting his purpose to<lb/>
                    his solid glory &amp; to the solid advantage of the State<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    I am not quite clear that I (too) have<lb/>
                    not been repeating to you your own book; but if<lb/>
                    I have you will forgive me because you will<lb/>
                    see that the thoughts are so incorporated with<lb/>
                    mine that I have "made them my own" - I am<lb/>
                    however determined to tell you something that<lb/>
                    is not in your book. - About a month ago at<lb/>
                    the assizes of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Mullingar_IE">Mullingar</placeName> a County Town near<lb/>
                    us a <del>man</del> criminal appeared in the dock, who<lb/>
                    had been committed to jail upon the charge of<lb/>
                    having stolen 5 apples on <add>All-hallows</add> <hi rend="underline">Hollantide Eve</hi>!!!!!<lb/>
                    - The judge waved his hand in sign of mercy<lb/>
                    &amp; discharged the prisoner without hearing one<lb/>
                    word but the charge against the criminal. What must<lb/>
                    have been the grand jury who found the Bill?<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    Criminals themselves frequently <choice><orig>ex-<lb/>
                    press</orig><reg>express</reg></choice> in this country with great naïveté their<lb/>
                    sense of the extravagant severity of the law<lb/>
                    &amp; true to their passion for blundering <add>-strong</add> even<lb/>
                    in death, turn that which was meant for <choice><orig>tra-<lb/>
                    gedy</orig><reg>tragedy</reg></choice> to farce - a woman who was lately <choice><orig>sentenc<lb/>
                    ed</orig><reg>sentenced</reg></choice> here by a judge in the usual form to be <choice><orig>hang-<lb/>
                    ed</orig><reg>hanged</reg></choice> drawn &amp; quartered <add>her heart to be taken out</add> embowelled &amp;c. forgetting<lb/>
                    that she could not feel after death exclaimed<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    "Oh Boo! Boo! my Lord I will never be able<lb/>
                    to bear the half of it!<lb/></p>
                
                
            </div>
        </body>
        <back> </back>
    </text>
</TEI>


